# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bigsby-medal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bigsby-medal/aberconway-medal] The **Aberconway Medal** is a medal of the Geological Society of London, formerly awarded annually by the Institution of Geologists.
[src:bigsby-medal/aberconway-medal] Since 1991, when the institution of geologists merged with the society, the medal has been awarded biennally by the Geological Society.
[src:bigsby-medal/aberconway-medal] The award was established with a gift from English China Clays and its chairman Charles McLaren, 3rd Baron Aberconway.
[src:bigsby-medal/aberconway-medal] It is normally awarded to individuals with no more than 25 years full-time equivalent experience to recognise distinction in the practice of applied or economic geology with special reference to work in industry.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] Smith was born in Watford, and went to school at Watford Grammar School for Boys.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] Smith went to university at St John's College, Cambridge, and graduated in 1959 with a B.A. in natural sciences.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] From 1959 to 1963 he was a graduate student in geology at Princeton University, where he completed a PhD thesis on the *Structure and stratigraphy of the northwest Whitefish Range, Lincoln County, Montana* under the supervision of John C.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] In 1963, Smith was appointed as a research assistant to Edward Bullard in the Department of Geodesy and Geophysics of the University of Cambridge.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] In 1964 he was appointed a demonstrator in the same department, and lecturer in 1971.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] His doctoral students included Michael Welland.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] Smith's Ph.D. thesis was a major contribution to stratigraphic understanding of the Belt Supergroup.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] Smith and his collaborators did significant research on plate tectonics, the tectonics of the Balkan peninsula (especially Greece), and the geological timescale.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] His 1965 paper *The fit of the continents around the Atlantic*, co-authored with Edward Bullard and Jim Everett has historic importance in the establishment of the validity of plate tectonics.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] Pickering, proposed a unifying explanation for Earth's icehouse periods during the past 620 million years.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] Smith's father was an engineer and inventor, who developed instruments for the Royal Navy during WWII.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] In 1962, Smith married Judy Walton, who worked for Princeton University Press at the time.
[src:bigsby-medal/alan-gilbert-smith] Smith died in 2017, and was survived by their daughter and granddaughter.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] He is a foreign member of the Russian Academy of Science.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] He is a recipient of Gustav-Steinmann-Medaille — the highest distinction of the Geologische Vereinigung e.V.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] Celal Şengör was born on 24 March 1955, in Istanbul, to a muhacir family from Rumelia.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] After graduating from Robert College, he received his BS (1978), MS (1979), PhD (1982) degrees from the State University of New York, Albany.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] He writes a weekly popular science column in the center-left daily *Cumhuriyet*.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] He is married and has a son. Şengör has been diagnosed with Asperger syndrome.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] Şengör is vocal in his support of the Turkish military and the 1980 military coup in Turkey.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] In a very controversial interview published on the website of *Radikal* newspaper, Şengör argued that the root cause of Turkey's political problems was the lack of an aristocratic class, which would lead the society in cultural life and politics.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] According to Şengör, the Turkish military is the only elite class in society, and their refinement and education make them qualified for a rule.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] Most controversially, he expressed his unqualified approval of every policy of the military regime between 1980 and 1982 in Turkey by asserting that being forced to eat excrement should not be regarded as torture.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] But later in his statement he stated that it would not be considered torture as it was not an ongoing action. Şengör later apologized for his remarks and claimed that he was misunderstood.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] Şengör also stated in an interview that he preferred monarchy to a republic or democracy, especially for judicial independence and against corruption.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] In this interview, referring to Plato for the ideal political system, he advocated the rule of a cultured elite against the rule of ordinary people.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] In H988, he received an honorary Doctorate from the University of Neuchâtel.
[src:bigsby-medal/ali-mehmet-celal-sengor] In 2012, he became a foreign member of the German Academy of Sciences Leopoldina.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] In 1870 he entered the Jesuit Training College at the old abbey of Maria Laach in the Eifel, and there, while engaged in studying philosophy and science, he became interested in the geology of the district, and especially in the volcanic rocks.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] Thenceforth he worked at chemistry and mineralogy, and qualified himself for those petrographical researches for which he was distinguished.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] In 1874 he became professor of chemistry and geology in the college of the Belgian Jesuits at Leuven, a few years later he was appointed one of the curators of the Royal Natural History Museum at Brussels, and in 1882 he relinquished his post at Louvain.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] In 1888 he was chosen professor of geology at the University of Ghent, and retained the post until the close of his life.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] Meanwhile, he had been ordained priest in 1877, and had intended to enter the Society of Jesus.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] He was known as the Abbé Renard; but, as remarked by Sir A.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] Geikie, as years passed, the longing for mental freedom grew ever stronger, until at last it overmastered all the traditions and associations of a lifetime, and he finally separated himself from the church of Rome.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] His first work, written in conjunction with Charles-Louis-Joseph-Xavier de la Vallée-Poussin (1827–1904), was the *Mémoire sur les caractères minéralogiques et stratigraphiques des roches dues plutoniennes de la Belgique et de l'Ardenne française* (1876).
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] In later essays and papers he dealt with the structure and mineral composition of many igneous and sedimentary rocks, and with the phenomena of metamorphism in Belgium and other countries.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] In acknowledgment of his work, the Bigsby Medal was awarded to him in 1885 by the Geological Society of London.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] Still more important were his later researches connected with the Challenger Expedition.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] The various rock specimens and oceanic deposits were submitted to him for examination in association with Sir John Murray, and their detailed observations were embodied in the *Report on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of* H.M.S.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] Rue Alphonse Renard, in western Ixelles, is named in his honor.
[src:bigsby-medal/alphonse-renard] In addition, the mineral renardite was named in his honor in 1928.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Williams was born in Aberdare, an industrial town in Rhondda Cynon Taf, South Wales, and attended Aberdare Boys' Grammar School.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] He was a keen sportsman in his youth, taking part in athletics and rugby, and had ambitions to join the Fleet Air Arm of the Royal Navy, although these were thwarted by a bout of tuberculosis in 1939, which confined him for a time to a sanitorium.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] He instead won a scholarship to study at University College of Wales, Aberystwyth, where he achieved a First in geology in 1939, and a PhD, studying Welsh Ordovician rocks and describing new species of brachiopods.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Whilst at Aberystwyth he served both as President of the institution's Students' Representative Council, and as National Vice-President of the National Union of Students.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] In 1948, he was appointed Lecturer in Geology at the University of Glasgow, but postponed this position to complete a two-year Harkness Fellowship at the Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C., working under leading brachiopod expert G.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Williams took up his post as Lecturer in Geology at the University of Glasgow in 1950, but remained only four years, moving in 1954 to the Chair in Geology at Queen's University Belfast.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Whilst at Belfast, he served as Dean of Science and as Secretary to the Academic Council, and from 1967 as Pro-Vice-Principal.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] He left Belfast in 1974 to succeed Fred Shotton as Lapworth Professor of Geology and Head of Department at the University of Birmingham, and two years later returned to Glasgow as Principal of the University.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Whilst at Belfast, Williams began focussing his research on brachiopods, introducing new techniques to study of the species, particularly transmission and scanning electron microscopy.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] At this time he also began work on the brachiopod volumes of the Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology, and at the 1990 International Brachiopod Congress, he agreed to co-ordinate a complete revision of these volumes.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Whilst Principal at Glasgow, he began expanding his research into the interrelationships between the soft tissues and hard shells of brachiopods in the new Palaeobiology Unit.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Williams was appointed Principal of the University of Glasgow in 1976, succeeding Sir Charles Wilson.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] He introduced new teaching practices to the University, using modern technology, and established what is now one of the leading departments of Computing Science in the UK, and is credited with improving the research rigour of the institution.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Despite his heavy load of administrative duties as Principal, Williams continued his research, publishing twenty refereed papers and holding three NERC grants.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Upon retiring as Principal in 1988, he created a Palaeobiology Unit to support his own continued research.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Sir Alwyn became President of the Royal Society of Edinburgh in 1985, serving until 1988.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Although his tenure lasted only three years, it included the purchase of the Society's landmark premises in George Street and the fostering of links with the Royal Society in London and the Royal Irish Academy, Williams also holding membership of both organisations.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] His leadership helped the RSE to develop its position and role as one of the leading academies of the British Isles.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] The Sir Alwyn Williams Building at the University of Glasgow was opened on 22 June 2007 by Professor Anne Glover, Chief Scientific Adviser for Scotland, and Williams's widow, Joan.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] It was an extension to the facilities of the Department of Computing Science, located between the Department's pre-existing accommodation, in a row of interconnected Victorian townhouses on Lilybank Gardens, and the 1968-built Queen Margaret Union building.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] The Building contains offices and laboratories as well as informal "break-out spaces".
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] The architectural style is strikingly modern, and building work also included construction of a pedestrianised plaza between University Gardens and Lilybank Gardens, connecting to the North doors of the Boyd Orr Building.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Construction lasted between 2005 and 2007, and cost £4M.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] The building was designed by Reiach and Hall Architects, who also built the University's Wolfson Medical School Building.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] In 2008, the building was briefly occupied by students protesting against violence in the Gaza Strip.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] Williams married Joan Bevan in 1949, with whom he had a son and a daughter, Professor Gareth Williams and Dr Sian Shepherd.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] The pair met while studying in Aberystwyth and married in Canada.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] The family lived in Pollokshields in the South of Glasgow.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] As well as his academic and administrative posts, Williams had a keen interest in the arts, and was chairman of the Committee on National Museums and Galleries in Scotland between 1979 and 1981.
[src:bigsby-medal/alwyn-williams-geologist] During this time he conducted a report on the National Museum of Antiquities, which led to the establishment of the Museum of Scotland.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] Growing up in Stonehaven along the eastern coast of Scotland, Smith was inspired to collect fossils after watching an episode of the television programme *Blue Peter* on fossil collection.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] In 1968, when on holiday in Shetland, he collected a complete fossil of a Devonian fish (*Dipterus valenciennesi*)—the specimen was put on display at the Shetland Museum in Lerwick.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] From 1973 to 1976, Smith studied geology at the University of Edinburgh, where he graduated with first class honours.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] In the summer of 1976, on the recommendation of palaeontologist Euan Clarkson, he received a Carnegie Award to study echinoid fossil distribution in the Aalenian (Inferior Oolite) of the Cheltenham region of Gloucestershire.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] In 1976, Smith matriculated as a graduate student in the biology department of the University of Exeter.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] In 1980, under the supervision of David Nichols (1930–2020), Smith received a Ph.D.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] Smith's Ph.D. thesis involved a breakthrough in echinoid functional morphology through his use of the scanning electron microscope combined with histological preparations and some *in vivo* research.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] He also published multiple papers regarding the links between echinoid skeletal histology and soft-tissue anatomy.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] From 1980 to 1982, he worked at the University of Liverpool as a research assistant to palaeontolgist Christopher R.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] At the Natural History Museum, London, Smith was a scientific officer from 1982 to 2012, when he retired.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] During his 30 years of employment at the museum, he published numerous papers on the phylogeny, systematics, and taxonomy of echinoderms, gaining an international reputation as a leading expert on echinoderm palaeontology.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] In 1985, he participated in Western scientists' first geological traverse of the Tibetan plateau.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] Furthermore, alongside co-author Claud William Wright, Smith authored a twelve-part series of monographs on British echinoid fossils of the Cretaceous.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] Smith's research also deals with methods of inferring patterns in evolutionary development from the fossil record.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] With biologist Colin Patterson, Smith pointed out possible pitfalls in interpreting the fossil record.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] Smith and colleagues assessed mass extinctions such as that at the Cretaceous/Tertiary transition from studies on spiny-shelled fossils.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] He conducted research on the earliest evolutionary origins of echinoderms and establishing the dates of the evolutionary origins of metazoan body morphologies.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] He also carried out comparative studies on evolution and species diversification using molecular biological methods and dealt with ancient DNA of fossil insects preserved in amber.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] Along with his active research output, Smith designed and created a web-based, echinoid-specific approach to systematic zoology and paleontology named "The Echinoid Directory," which was sponsored by the Natural History Museum, London.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] The website was driven by the international community of echinoid scientists who contributed via a web interface.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] There were over 2,000 species pages and over 10,000 specimen illustrations.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] As of February 2025, the website is no longer functional and has been taken offline.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] The Linnean Society of London awarded Andrew B.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] Smith in 1993 the Linnean Society Bicentenary Medal and in 2005 the Zoology Medal.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] The Geological Society of London award him in 1995 the Bigsby Medal and in 2002 the Lyell Medal.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] Smith was elected in 1996 a Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh and in 2002 a Fellow of the Royal Society.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] He received in 2004 the Palaeontological Association's Golden Trilobite Award (for best website) and in 2020 the association's Lapworth Medal.
[src:bigsby-medal/andrew-benjamin-smith] In 2005 he was elected a corresponding member of the *Paläontologische Gesellschaft*.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] Trueman was born in Nottingham, the son of Elijah Trueman, a lacemaker, and his wife Thirza Newton Cottee.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] He was educated at High Pavement School in Nottingham from 1899 to 1911, then became a student teacher at Huntington Street School, Nottingham.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] He entered University College Nottingham in 1912 with a grant as a teacher in training, and studied Geology under H.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] Swinnerton, graduating B.Sc. with first-class honours in 1914.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] He gained an M.Sc. in 1916 and doctorate (D.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] Sc.) in 1918, all from University College Nottingham.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] Trueman's first academic post was as Assistant Lecturer at University College, Cardiff, from late 1917 until 1920.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] From 1920 on, he was lecturer and head of the Department of Geology at the newly established University College, Swansea, and was appointed Professor of Geology and head of the Department of Geography in 1930.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] In 1933, he was appointed Channing Wills Professor of Geology at the University of Bristol, where he also served as Dean of the Faculty of Science for three years.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] Amongst his students at that time was the young future Professor L.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] In 1937, he was appointed chair of geology at the University of Glasgow until 1946, when he was succeeded by his student Neville George.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] In 1938 he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] His proposers were John Walton, George Tyrrell, John Weir and James Kendall.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] In 1942 he was also elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of London.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] From 1946 until 1953 he served on the University Grants Committee, and was chair from 1949.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] From 1945 to 1947, he was president of the Geological Society of London.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] He also served as chairman of the British Association Committee on the Teaching of Geology in Schools, as president of the Geological Section of the Bristol Naturalists' Society, and president of the Glasgow Geological Society.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] He was knighted by King George VI in 1951.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] In 1920, he married Florence Kate Offler.
[src:bigsby-medal/arthur-elijah-trueman] He received four honorary LL.D. degrees, from Glasgow, Rhodes, Wales, and Leeds.
[src:bigsby-medal/bigsby-medal] The **Bigsby Medal** is a medal of the Geological Society of London established by John Jeremiah Bigsby.
